<div class="bibEntry"><p class="bib">136. Chevreul, M. E. The Principles of Harmony and Contrast of Colors and Their Applications to the Arts. Edited by Faber Birren. New York: Van Nostrand Reinhold, 1967. 256 pp. Index, endnotes/footnotes, glossary, B/W illus., color illus. </p><p class="annot">First published in French in 1839, this historic work influenced19th-century painters, including Delacroix and Seurat. Of greatest importance are Chevreulâ€™s laws of simultaneous contrast, color harmony, and visual mixtures. Each law is explained in detail with references and color illustrations. Color problems in painting and tapestry and practical use of color in home furnishings are also considered by Chevreul. The introduction and annotations by Faber Birren make the work more accessible to modem readers. </p></div>
